article.description:
Cheryl Ford scored 15 points and grabbed eight
rebounds to help the Detroit Shock rout the Chicago Sky 76-49 on
Friday night.
article.headline: Sky suffer Shock-ingly bad loss to Detroit
article.linkText: Sky suffer Shock-ingly bad loss at hands of Detroit
article.story:
CHICAGO (AP)-- The Detroit Shock scored the first 17 points of
the game Friday night and never looked back.

Cheryl Ford scored 15 points and grabbed eight rebounds to help
the Detroit Shock rout the Chicago Sky 76-49.

Deanna Nolan added 12 points and four assists for the Shock
(20-9), who won for the sixth time in eight games. Plenette
Pierson had 15 as Detroit pulled within three games of the Eastern
Conference-leading Connecticut Sun.

"We're trying to get homecourt advantage in the playoffs,"
Ford said. "We knew we had to come out and play hard from the
beginning."

Stacey Lovelace scored 10 points for Chicago (4-25), which lost
for the 11th time in 12 games. Candice Dupree added nine points as
the Sky fell to 0-3 against Detroit.

The 49 points was a franchise-low for Chicago.

"I think this is the first game that I can say we looked like
an expansion team," Sky coach Dave Cowens said. "I think in the
other ones [losses] we represented well, but tonight we got run out
of the gym."

Detroit opened the game with a 17-0 run and built a 29-6 lead at
the end of the first quarter. Chicago struggled on the offensive
end, hitting only one of its first 14 shots in the period.

Detroit extended the lead to 49-19 at the half, hitting 50
percent of its shots.

The Shock then took a 66-27 lead into the fourth quarter before
Chicago outscored Detroit 22-10 in the final period.

The Shock made 50 percent of their shots and were 12-for-12 from
the free throw line in the quarter.

"Our defense was pretty solid but they didn't make any shots,"
said Detroit head coach Bill Laimbeer "We got all the rebounds and
just ran down and scored."

Detroit, which lost at New York 75-67 on Thursday to fall to 3-4
in the opener of back-to-backs, improved to 7-0 in the second game.
